Some terminologies in trees-based models

  • Decision Trees
    • a flowchart-like structure in which each internal node represents a test on an attribute
    • each branch represents the outcome of the test
    • each leaf (terminal) node represents a class label
    • Root Node - starting point of the tree
  • Classification Trees
    • used when the target variable is categorical
    • i.e.Â the outcome is a class label
  • Regression Trees
    • used when the target variable is continuous
    • i.e.Â the outcome is a continuous value
  • Data Scientists often use the term tree-based models to refer to both classification and regression trees
    • so-called Classification And Regression Trees (CART)

Benefits from using trees-based model

  • the flowchart-like tree structure is in a human-readable format

  • This provides insight into how and why the model works or doesnât work well for a particular task

  • This also makes decision trees particularly appropriate for applications where

    • classification mechanism needs to be transparent for legal reasons
    • the results need to be shared with others to inform future business/research practice

Some examples of its potential uses

  • Credit scoring models
    • the criteria that cause an applicant to be rejected need to be clearly documented and free from bias
  • Marketing studies of customer behavior
    • satisfaction or churn
    • for product improvement or advertising agencies
  • Diagnosis of medical conditions
    • laboratory measurements
    • symptoms
    • rates of disease progression

Scenarios that tree-based models might not fit

  • many nominal features with many levels

  • a large number of numeric features

    • result in a very large number of decisions and an overly complex tree
    • make decision trees (easily) overfit data

A brief discussion on Divide and Conquer approach

  • trees are built using recursive partition splitting

  • this approach is often regarded as divide and conquer (do you believe it?)

    • it splits the data into subsets
    • which are then split repeatedly into even smaller subsets
    • and so on and so forth
    • until the process stops
    • when the algorithm determines the data within the subsets are sufficiently homogenous, or another stopping criterion has been met
  • For a classification tree, we predict that each observation belongs to the most commonly occurring class of training observations in the region to which it belongs

The process of building a decision tree (in more detail)

  1. the root node represents the entire dataset

  2. the decision tree algorithm must choose a feature to split upon

    • (ideally) it chooses the feature most predictive of the target class

  3. the dataset is partitioned into groups according to the distinct values of this feature

    • the first set of tree branches is formed

  4. Working down each branch, the algorithm continues to divide and conquer the data

    • choosing the best candidate feature each time to create another decision node
    • until a stopping criterion is reached

  5. Divide and conquer might stop at a node if:

    • All (or nearly all) of the examples at the node have the same class
    • There are no remaining features to distinguish among the examples
    • The tree has grown to a predefined size limit

Some details of the implementation of classification trees

  • In the classification trees with binary splits algorithm, the classification error rate is a natural choice for criterion to minimize

  • it means the fraction of the training observations in that region that do not belong to the most common class:

\[ E = 1 â \max_k(\hat{p}_{mk}) \] \(\quad\) \(\hat{p}_{mk}\) represents the proportion of training observations in the \(m\)th region that are from the \(k\)th class

  • for those who are more rigorous in definition
    • \(\hat{p}_{mk}=\frac{1}{n_m} \sum_{x_i \in R_m} \indicator{y_i=k}\)
    • \(n_m\) is the total number of training observations in the \(m\)th region (\(R_m\)), i.e.Â \(n_m=\sum^n_{i=1} \indicator{x_i \in R_m}\)
  • In practice, the classification error rate might not be a good criterion to build a tree
    • it is not sufficiently sensitive for tree-growing
  • the Gini index and Entropy are more likely to be used

  • \(k(m)=\arg \max_k \hat{p}_{mk}\) is the most common class label in the \(m\)th region

  • $E=_{x_i R_m} (y_i k(m))= 1- k (*) $

  • it is not sufficiently sensitive for tree-growing

    • especially when the classes are imbalanced

The Gini index

The Gini index is defined by

\[ G = \sum\limits^K_{k=1} \hat{p}_{mk}(1 â \hat{p}_{mk}) \]

  • The Gini index is a measure of total variance across the \(K\) classes

  • Gini takes on a small value if all of the \(\hat{p}_{mk}\)âs are close to 0 or 1

  • the Gini index is referred to as a measure of node purity

    • a small value indicates that a node contains predominantly observations from a single class
  • Gini represents the variance of a binomial distribution
    • the diagonal of the multinomial variance covariance matrix for > 2 classes

Entropy

  • Entropy is given by

\[ D = â \sum\limits^K_{k=1} \hat{p}_{mk} \log \hat{p}_{mk} \]

  • Entropy is a measure of node impurity
    • a small value indicates that a node contains predominantly observations from a single class

  • the Entropy is closely related to the Gini index

  • the Gini index and the Entropy are very similar numerically

  • a large value indicates that the observations are more evenly spread across the classes

  • the base for \(\log\) can be 2 (measured in bits), \(e\) (measured in nats), or 10 (measured in dits/bans)

  • \(\log \frac{1}{\hat{p}_{mk}}\) is the information content of the \(k\)th class in the \(m\)th region

    • it measures the surprise of outcome \(k\) in region \(m\)
      • if \(\hat{p}_{mk}=1, \log \frac{1}{\hat{p}_{mk}}=0\), not surprising at all
      • if \(\hat{p}_{mk}=0.5, \log \frac{1}{\hat{p}_{mk}}=1\), quite surprising
      • if \(\hat{p}_{mk}=0, \log \frac{1}{\hat{p}_{mk}}=\infty\), very surprising
    • entropy is the average level of surprise (uncertainty or information) across all classes

  • Entropy in the information theory was introduced by Claude Shannonn in his 1948 landmark paper âA Mathematical Theory of Communicationâ, and measures the disorder of a random system

    • in our case, a random variable or a dataset
    • D with base 2 in log gives the average (genuine) information in the unit of bits of a random system

  • Gini index and entropy are also more sensitive to variations in the two child-node probabilities

    • \(\{\hat{p}_{m_L k(m_L)}, \hat{p}_{m_R k(m_R)} \}\)
    • compared to the classification error rate
    • so are recommended to grow the tree

  • They are differentiable, so more amenable to numerical optimization than misclassification error

  • Since \(p_2 = 1 -p_1\), \(G = p_1 (1 - p_1) + p_2 (1 - p_2) = 2p_1 (1 -p_1)\) is symmetric about \(p_1 = 0.5\)

    • with \(G = 0.5\) when \(p_1 = 0.5\) and \(G = 0\) when \(p_1 = 0\)

  • \(D = p_1 \log p_1 + p_2 \log p_2\) is also symmetric with \(D = \log_2 2 = 1\) when \(p_1 = 0.5\) and \(D = 0\) when \(p_1 = 0\) (by the convention \(0 \cdot \log 0 = 0\)) i.e., when \(p_1 = 0.5\), the system has the maximal disorder

    • This also indicates that entropy can be used to quantify the similarity or difference in the probabilities of the outcome

  • For example to compare misclassification rate and entropy, consider a dataset with 120 observations, 70 in class 1 and 50 in class 2

    • the misclassification error is \(E = 40/120 = 1/3\)
    • the entropy is \(D = 0.02\)
    • the misclassification error is 0.33, while the entropy is 0.02
    • the entropy is more sensitive to the distribution of the classes

  • If misclassification error is used, then \(\Delta E = 1/3 - (70/120 \cdot 28/70 + 50/120 \cdot 12/50) = 0\)

    • so the first splitting would not be conducted

  • If entropy is used, then \(\Delta D = 0.02 > 0\), so the first splitting would be conducted

  • [ E = ( ) - ( + ) = 0, ]

  • so the first splitting would not be conducted.

  • If entropy is used, then

\[ \Delta D = \left( \frac{40}{120} \log \frac{120}{40} + \frac{80}{120} \log \frac{120}{80} \right) - \left( \frac{70}{120} \left( \frac{28}{70} \log \frac{70}{28} + \frac{42}{70} \log \frac{70}{42} \right) + \frac{50}{120} \left( \frac{12}{50} \log \frac{50}{12} + \frac{38}{50} \log \frac{50}{38} \right) \right) = 0.02 > 0 \]

  • so the first splitting would be conducted

  • Why can this happen?

    • Entropy is concave in \(p_1\) while misclassification error is linear in \(p_1\) when $ p_1 $

Regression Trees - Baseball Salary Example

  • a regression tree for predicting the log salary of a baseball player

    • based on the number of years that he has played in the major leagues and the number of hits that he made in the previous year

  • At a given internal node, the label (of the form \(X_j < t_k\)) indicates the left-hand branch emanating from that split

    • the right-hand branch corresponds to \(X_j â¥ t_k\)

  • For instance, the split at the top of the tree results in two large branches

    • The left-hand branch corresponds to Years < 4.5
    • the right-hand branch corresponds to Years â¥ 4.5

  • The tree has two internal nodes and three terminal nodes, or leaves

  • The number in each leaf is the mean of the response for the observations that fall there

  • the tree stratifies the players into three regions of predictor space
    • \(R_1 = \{X|Years < 4.5 \}\),
    • \(R_2 = \{X|Years â¥ 4.5, Hits < 117.5 \}\)
    • \(R_3 = \{X|Years â¥ 4.5, Hits â¥ 117.5 \}\)

  • Years is the most important factor in determining Salary, and players with less experience earn lower salaries than more experienced players

  • Given that a player is less experienced, the number of Hits that he made in the previous year seems to play little role in his Salary

  • But among players who have been in the major leagues for five or more years, the number of Hits made in the previous year does affect Salary

    • players who made more Hits last year tend to have higher salaries

  • Surely an over-simplification, but compared to a regression model, it is easy to display, interpret and explain

A bit details of the tree-building process

  • divide the predictor space (the set of possible values for \(X_1, X_2, . . . , X_p\) )
    • into \(J\) distinct and non-overlapping regions, \(R_1, R_2, . . . , R_J\)
  • For every observation that falls into the region \(R_j\), the same prediction is made
    • the mean of the response values for the training observations in \(R_j\)
  • in the process, the algorithm divides the predictor space into high-dimensional rectangles (box)
    • this offer simplicity and ease of interpretation of the resulting predictive model
  • the goal is to find boxes \(R_1, R_2, . . . , R_J\) that minimize the mean squared error of the response variable within each box

\[ \sum_{j=1}^J \sum_{i \in R_j} (y_i - \hat{y}_{R_j})^2 \]

\(\quad\) where \(\hat{y}_{R_j}\) is the mean response for the training observations in the \(j^{th}\) box

  • the goal is to partition the data into boxes that balance homogeneity within boxes and distinctness among boxes

A bit details of the tree-building process

  • In practice, the recursive binary splitting take a top-down, greedy approach (~ divide and conquer)
    • we do not go into details the difference between the two approaches
  • top-down
    • it begins at the top of the tree and then successively splits the predictor space
    • each split is indicated via two new branches further down on the tree
  • greedy
    • at each step of the tree-building process, the best split is made at that particular step
    • instead of looking ahead and picking a split that will lead to a better tree in some future step

  • it is computationally infeasible to consider every possible partition of the feature space into J boxes

  • Multiway splits into more than two groups fragment the data too quickly

    • leaving insufficient data at the next level down

  • Since multiway splits can be achieved by a series of binary splits, the latter are preferred

  • here are the steps
    • the algorithm searches over all predictors and all possible cut-points for each predictor
    • the predictor and cut-point that results in the lowest mean squared error are chosen
    • the data are split into two regions, and the process is repeated on each of the two regions
    • the tree is grown recursively until a stopping criterion is met
  • the stopping criterion might be
    • maximum depth of the tree
    • minimum number of observations in each terminal node
    • minimum reduction in the mean squared error resulting from the split
  • predict the response for a given test observation using the mean of the training observations in the region to which that test observation belongs

Pruning a tree

  • a tree that is too large might lead to overfitting
    • The splitting process may produce good predictions on the training set, but is likely to overfit the data, leading to poor test set performance
  • One strategy is to grow the tree only so long as the decrease in the RSS due to each split exceeds some (high) threshold
    • this strategy will result in smaller trees
    • however, it is too short-sighted
      • a seemingly worthless split early on in the tree might be followed by a very good split â that is, a split that leads to a large reduction in RSS later on
  • Another strategy is to grow a very large tree \(T_0\), and then prune it back in order to obtain a subtree
    • in practice, this leads to a lower test error rate
    • the cost complexity pruning algorithm (also known as weakest link pruning) provides an automatic way to prune the tree

  • The process described above may produce good predictions on the training set, but is likely to overfit the data, leading to poor test set performance. Why?

  • Imagine a tree with one observation in each terminal node. What is our training error?

  • A smaller tree with fewer splits (that is, fewer regions \(R_1, . . . , R_J\)) might lead to lower variance and better interpretation at the cost of a little bias

  • One possible alternative to the process described above is to grow the tree only so long as the decrease in the RSS due to each split exceeds some (high) threshold

    • This strategy will result in smaller trees, but is too short-sighted
      • a seemingly worthless split early on in the tree might be followed by a very good split â that is, a split that leads to a large reduction in RSS later on

  • Cost complexity pruning â also known as weakest link pruning

    • the algorithm considers a sequence of trees indexed by a nonnegative tuning parameter \(\alpha\)
    • for each value of \(\alpha\), there corresponds a subtree \(T \subset T_0\) such that
      • \(\sum\limits_{m=1}^{|T|} \sum\limits_{i:x_i \in R_m} (y_i - \hat{y}_{R_m})^2 + \alpha |T|\) is as small as possible

\(\quad\) where \(|T|\) is the number of terminal nodes of the tree \(T\), \(R_m\) is the rectangle corresponding to the \(m^{th}\) terminal node, and \(\hat{y}_{R_m}\) is the predicted response associated with \(R_m\)

  • The tuning parameter Î± controls a trade-off between the subtreeâs complexity and its fit to the training data
    • \(Î± = 0\) corresponds to minimizing training error (will choose the largest tree, all pure nodes
    • Large \(Î±\) results in small trees
  • We select an optimal value \(\hat{Î±}\) using cross-validation.
    • We then return to the full data set and obtain the subtree corresponding to \(\hat{Î±}\)

Tree vs Linear Models

Tree vs Linear Models

Advantages of Trees

  • Trees are very easy to explain to people

    • they are even easier to explain than linear regression

  • Some people believe that decision trees more closely mirror human decision-making than do the regression and other classification approaches

    • e.g., âMiddle-aged low-skilled self-employed male workers who reside in a small-flat unit in Sham Shui Po have the highest probability of defaulting on their credit card paymentsâ could be a statement based on a tree model

  • Trees can be displayed graphically, and are easily interpreted even by a non-expert

  • Trees can easily handle qualitative predictors without the need to create dummy variables

Tree vs Linear Models

Disadvantages of Trees

  • trees generally do not have the same level of predictive accuracy as some of the other regression and classification approaches

  • they can be prone to overfitting the data

    • especially if the tree is allowed to grow without pruning, or the minimum number of samples per leaf set too low

  • trees are locally optimal

    • a greedy algorithm is used to build the tree
    • it may not necessarily result in the best tree

  • Lack of smoothness of the prediction surface in the regression setting

  • trees can be very non-robust

    • a small change in the data can cause a large change in the final estimated tree
    • high variance

  • As a remedy for the the variance problem, bagging, random forests, and boosting have been proposed

  • Bagging and Random Forests reduce this variance by averaging many trees
  • These methods grow multiple trees which are then combined to yield a single consensus prediction
  • By aggregating many decision trees, the predictive performance of trees can be substantially improved at the expense of some loss interpretation

Appendix - Cross-Entropy

  • Cross-entropy is a measure from the field of information theory
    • it is used to quantify the difference between two probability distributions
    • it is commonly used in machine learning as a loss function
  • The cross-entropy of the distribution \(q\) relative to the distribution \(p\) is defined as

\[ H (p, q) = - â^M_{m=1} p_m \log (q_m), \]

\(\quad\) where \((q_1, \cdots , q_M)\) are the predicted probabilities while \((p_1, \dots, p_M )\) are the true probabilities

  • In information theory, the cross-entropy is the average message length to code data generated from \(p\) under \(q\) (in bits when the base for log is 2)
    • if the predicted probabilities match the true probabilities, the cross-entropy is equal to entropy, and the length is shortest
  • The cross-entropy between two probability distributions \(p\) and \(q\) over the same underlying set of events measures the average number of bits needed to identify an event drawn from the set, if a coding scheme is used that is optimized for an âunnaturalâ probability distribution \(q\), rather than the âtrueâ distribution \(p\)
